<font color="#FF0000">HOMELESS VETS</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov 10 20:50:17 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Cook,<br>
    I fully understand your concern about the negative stereotypes the Vietnam Veteran has had to struggle against and the quandary you speak of above - &quot;accept it and it brings us shame, deny it and it brings us shame.&quot;  <br>
     <br>
    The shame doesn't belong to the Vet in the first place - The shame doesn't belong to a person in need of help, it belongs to those who turn their back on them.  If we cast away or judge an entire group of men who went to war for their country then the shame belongs to all of the citizens of this country.  We must look at our ability to &quot;write off&quot; entire groups of people (vets, homeless, minorities, troubled kids, welfare mothers) to make life simpler for our confused minds and restless consciences.  Everyone is overwhelmed with the problems of this country, trying to find simple solutions to complex problems, some want to throw money at them, some want to throw all the &quot;trouble makers&quot; off on an island somewhere and most want to bury their heads in the sand with convenient stereotypes that ease their guilt. I believe it is the DUTY of all of us who claim to love our country and reap its benefits to give back.  Not just by throwing money at people (though some programs need financial backing), but by active involvement, day to day caring for one another and the realization that all of us are in this together and quality of our happiness is collective.  All the finger pointing and blame we tend to do does nothing to change the fact that we are ALL brought down by these sorrows.  I believe our only choice is to take on the misery in our country like we were facing the enemy.<br>
     You once said something about your love for the old fashioned ideals of this country and the joy of the family holidays such as the Fourth of July.  I feel the same yearning for our innocence - I tried to recapture those traditions for my three daughters, but it was hard to maintain the same carefree feeling we had as children, when our children are blatantly aware of all the ugliness that exists outside of our walls.  We can't put it back in the box and if we try to throw them away there's another larger generation of problems right behind them. We can't go back, we have to accept that our country is going through growing pains and do as our forefathers have done - to see a better future - our only choice is to help fix the ills, if we want something better for our grandchildren.  <br>
     <br>
You are rare in that you have your cause and you are seeking ways of healing the wounds that continue to be inflicted on the Vietnam Vet, whom I agree are some of the most deserving (along with children's causes) of our support.  <br><br>
I don't think these figures will have much effect on the bigoted attitudes people in this country have formed over the years (everyone seems to have stories of knowing a vet who went balistic or couldn't control his anger on the job). But the good news is that what will change those attitudes and (already is) is the number of vets, like yourself who are giving something back even after they've already given their all for their country in war.  What I keep hearing more and more in conversation is about the vets who are going back to Vietnam to assist the Vietnamese, and the vet who risked his own life to save a childs, or the vets who started the treaty to ban land mines or the local vet, high school teacher who was changing the lives of many teens.  These are the stories that change opinions - this is where your true power lies.  As Vietnam Vets become more and more recognized for current deeds, they automatically brings honor and attention to their past as well as empathy and concern for those vets who still need our help.   <br>
    <br>
A few years ago, I took a group of adolescent girls to Europe for a soccer tournament and sat them down and explained that people tend to make sweeping judgements of entire groups of people based on their limited experiences.  Therefore, I expected above exemplary behavior, because they each were now representatives of my country! So, fair or not, each of you vets are ambassadors for your brothers and your responsibility is still greater than most.  We may be mere drops of the ocean, but if we collectively choose a direction we have the power to turn the tide. <br><br>
I work a 4 day work week and try to volunteer on my day off.  Your letter has inspired me to look into the needs of the Union Gospel Mission - I'll keep you informed.<br><br>
ANNE   
